div.div:
The interface definition looks like a set of filters. Simpler
interfaces may only need one filter, if the attribute is already defined
on the objects being filtered.
Other interfaces with nested elements may need multiple filters, such as types, which have networks of super/sub types.

div.div: Using parameters of the original objects as a set of filters
Attributes like width & height, number of objects & position, symmetry & intersection, number of corners & layer

Attributes form a good foundation for an interface because attributes often represent the collapse of many other attributes into one output attribute, making them a good tool to use as a filter since they're already the output of a filter of many other objects

div.div: Framing objects as a set of filters involves finding the specific sub-interfaces present in a space.
Just like type & intent are general cross-system interfaces, object/attribute/rule are specific interfaces for the system and network objects
- conditions are clearly mappable to filters (the restricting condition is the filter)
- processes apply a filter set from input to output, and therefore have an emergent filter
- relationships are objects calculated to be equivalent, and are filters generated on the equivalence function interface

div.div: A symmetry is an axis of transformation that leaves some attributes unchanged

Example: rotation around a dimension axis (holding y-axis value constant, to lock position attribute) leaves other dimensions of the object (radius, origin point) & dependent attributes (shape, volume) on those dimensions unchanged
You could frame the symmetry as the center of transformation (axis, origin), or the function generating that center (rotation).

Transformations can also be around other objects than an attribute: transforming an object around an interface, type, or standardizing function might change its position or type but hold other attributes constant.

In the function interface examples below, the structure of the combination remains the same, but the object identities/types, and extra objects using that structure as a foundation change, so the items were transformed around the combination function symmetry & the structural symmetry emerging from the combination definition.

The center is a common object to start with when looking for symmetries - manifesting as an average or a point of reflection around which some attribute (measured by distance to point) wouldn't change.
A symmetry filters the types of change possible so that an object can be identified/evaluated by the metric of symmetry (circle position).

Property collisions can also be predicted using this interface: predicting the property collisions of a circle & a triangle's boundaries when their centers are aligned, where the circle & triangle having attribute values within a particular set, is possible using the definition of the map between corner/angle/etc and tangent/coundary/intersection, using the common center symmetry as a connection link.

Just knowing the definition of the objects circle/triangle and the sub-objects of an angle, corner, etc would enable you to predict that when centered, the circle & triangle will have intersecting boundary attribute values when their centers are aligned.

You can also calculate the degree of difference involved in different object combinations given their symmetries - estimating whether the triangle or the square will be a better approximation or generator of the circle is possible given the target metric (good approximator or generator) and the symmetries connecting them.

div.div: It's possible to derive the existence of other interfaces given change types.

When identifying symmetries in the bio-system, a structural symmetry might appear to be the spine, until you identify that some asymmetries are present, like the position of different organs on either side. Then you would know that sub-type of that symmetry is needed (the chiral structure symmetry). You'd also be able to derive that the spine wasn't the core symmetry but rather an output of it, so the existence of a symmetry up an abstraction layer (the center symmetry) is implied in order to generate the spine, given the collapse of other objects/rules/attributes to the center symmetry.
How do you identify a false symmetry that isn't a real symmetry?

Either it violates the properties of a symmetry, or you're missing some information about other attributes that don't follow the rules of a symmetry, or you assumed that having similar motion indicates having a similar symmetry, but one was a special case where one attribute had a null value.

div.div: You can see where interfaces overlap (reason is a function of difference, so the difference between inout/output or the difference exerted by a function relate to the idea of difference, which relates to the structural interface at its definitions of structural difference (distance, position, etc) and the change interface, where difference is an output or input or interim state of change.

These overlaps can be framed as pathways between interfaces - once you standardize to the difference interface, you can easily re-standardize to the change, structural, reason, or function interfaces, where difference has a clear mapping to an implementation in those interfaces.

div.div:
The core functions in the middle are explanatory of all other functions in the system, unless variance injections occur, in which case they may be bad at explaining changes.
The outer functions (applications for greater intents like those relevant to users) are generated by paths between inner functions, but they may encapsulate more relevant information to users.
The interim functions are the least visible in terms of their side effects and interaction patterns, because they are combinations of core functions (meaning there are more of them) and they're also used as combination function inputs to generate the outer layer of application functions.
If there is a clear mapping between interim functions and outer/core functions, the interim layer may be the best place to start when debugging an application. If there isn't a clear mapping, the map should be generated to look for overlapping/repeated/unnecessary functionality as well as diverging intent combinations & other function metadata.
If the bug is relevant to a certain application function, the trajectory from core to interim to that application function as well as the trajectory from application functions interacting with the buggy application function are the best places to start when debugging that particular error.
If there is a buggy application or interim function set and each function in the buggy set has a common trajectory or function, that's the best place to start when debugging.
If errors of a certain type have a pattern in their trajectory between functions or function layers or other function metadata, that's the best place to start when debugging errors of that type.
If there is a different framing function to generate the functionality maps (using position in function trajectory rather than generative functions as a way to frame function layers, where the inner layer represents functions at the first step in a function trajectory, then finding the best framing function is the best place to start. Different framing functions highlight different differences, so that should be pre-computed & applied to the function trajectory problem space.

div.div: Symmetry: attributes that don't change under certain transforms, so that transformed objects don't lose information for those attributes.
Example symmetry: shapes rotated around an axis.
Vertex: point where changes aggregate, determining the identity of the object

Example vertex: in the sequence 2, 4, 6, 8 the vertex is 2. In the sequence 2,3,4,6,8 the vertexes are 2, 3, and 4 (the numbers needed to predict the rest of the sequence with reasonable certainty, including the distortion from the clear base 2 pattern.

Paradox: attributes whose metadata contradict each other, given their conflicting attribute paths, implications, or rules, but which can be simultaneously true when their rules/attributes are abstracted or applied within a context.
Example paradox: momentum & position measurements of an electron.

div.div: When change types collide, it usually produces more change, which stabilizes when efficient connections are found - these efficient connections form an interface, or a platform for change, on which change can occur in smaller increments which don't invalidate the change platform.

Each new interface continues supporting change, which attracts more change, until the changes start interacting in compounding ways that create too much change to support, at which point a new interface is necessary.

The direction of interface development is not always clear, and not always linear. There may be multiple interfaces supporting the same change types or change sets, and there may be alternatives that the changes on one interface can fall back on if one interface collapses to smaller dimensions or isn't able to support the changes by adding new dimensions. Changes on interfaces can also revert to prior or standard/base interfaces in the event of an interface collapse.

For example, with evolution, the development of interfaces changed between interacting systems, rule sets, and type sets, and is due for another interface since many species produced by evolution invalidate/neutralize each other because the specific implementation of evolution interfaces created a system that couldn't support enough change to allow the various change types to coexist.
Whether the filter interface was the initial interface is unclear, but several interfaces can be used to generate the filter interface, and vice versa.

The direction of causation between molecules and our observable layers may be in reverse - the molecular interfaces develops a new subatomic particle whenever the change rate/types/sets in the universe demand it. The reason that these subatomic particles are difficult to measure might not be optimization/efficiency but protecting the components that could create variance cascades, with security layers. If a subatomic particle is measured or added that the current change platforms can't support (given the information or causation provided by the measurement or new particle change types), it may invalidate the whole system.

The reason change handlers attract change is because the change's low-cost stable state is itself the way it is, so if the change-handler develops a handler (receptor) for that change the way it is, then the change can stay how it is rather than stabilizing to another state or dispresing. Good change handlers (interfaces/platforms for change) can abstract their handlers and create receptors for any change shepe/type on demand at change-encounter time.
How does change leak into othr interfaces or create new interafces, when one change platofrm can't handle a change type or degree?

For example, the major histocompatibility complex is a DNA region that codes cell surface proteins in the immune system, and is specific to vertebrates. If the spine acts as an interface/platform for change to develop on, the histocompatability complex could have evolved as a change handler for the change types that the vertebrate (or subsequent developed interfaces) supports.

Information is anything that stays constant, like a rule that doesn't change with respect to time - interfaces may only be useful for a certain time interval before they're invalidated, so it's important to be able to identify new interfaces & core functions & other interface metadata on the fly. Predicting change with respect to change & up is necessary for anticipating interfaces before they can be used to host changes.
